Not at all. What I&#x27;m saying is that /bin/sh has idiosyncratic, incomplete language syntax and semantics (mostly for historical reasons). For example, variable comparison is not built in but rather is dependent upon the external [ (or test). It would be hard to call a language &#x27;complete&#x27; when it doesn&#x27;t even support variable equality testing.<p>Whatever you think of Windows/MS/etc, Powershell is a decently-well-designed, complete language with a number of useful, convenient constructs. For example, here is a native Powershell hashmap (that can be looped over, etc.):<p><pre><code>  $states = @{&quot;Washington&quot; = &quot;Olympia&quot;; &quot;Oregon&quot; = &quot;Salem&quot;; California = &quot;Sacramento&quot;}
</code></pre>
Nice, no?
